{{about||the current Chicago Opera House|Civic Opera House (Chicago)|other references to opera in Chicago|List of Opera Houses in Chicago}}
{{Infobox building |name = Chicago Opera House |image = ChicagoOperaHouse.jpg |image_size = 220px |caption = The Chicago Opera House ca. 1885-95 |completion_date = 1885 |building_type = Offices and Theater |location = [[Chicago]], USA |coordinates = {{coord|41.8830|-87.6313|type:landmark_region:US-IL|display=inline,title}} |antenna_spire = |roof = |top_floor = |floor_count = |floor_area = |destruction_date = 1912 |architect = [[Cobb and Frost]] }}
The '''Chicago Opera House''', was a theater complex in [[Chicago, Illinois]], designed by the architectural firm of [[Cobb and Frost]].<ref name=condit>{{cite book| first=Carl W.| last=Condit| title=The Chicago School of Architecture| publisher=University of Chicago Press| date=15 November 1998| pages=59–60| isbn=978-0226114552}}</ref> The Chicago Opera House building took the cue provided by the [[Metropolitan Opera]] of New York as a mixed-used building: it housed both a theater and unrelated offices, used to subsidize the cost of the theater building. The theater itself was located in the middle of the complex and office structures flanked each side.<ref name="condit"/> The entire complex was known as the "Chicago Opera House Block," and was located at the Southwest corner of West Washington Avenue and North Clark Street.
The Chicago Opera House was opened to the public on August 18, 1885. The first performance in the new theater was of ''[[Hamlet]]'' starring Thomas W. Keene.<ref>{{cite news| title=The New Chicago Opera House| work=[[The New York Times]]| date=August 19, 1885| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1885/08/19/archives/the-new-chicago-opera-house.html| subscription=yes}}</ref> From 1887 to 1890, the Chicago Opera House served as the official observation location for recording the climate of the city of Chicago by the [[National Weather Service]].<ref>{{cite web| title=History of the Chicago and Rockford weather observation sites| url=http://www.weather.gov/lot/observation_history| publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]| accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref>
The theater suffered a fire in December 1888, which mainly damaged portions of the roof. However, the roof was repaired, and most of the exterior of the building remained undamaged. During its existence, the Chicago Opera House was the site of the premiere of several successful musicals such as ''[[Sinbad (1891 musical)|Sinbad]]'' and ''[[The Arabian Nights]]''.<ref>{{cite news| title=A Big Theatre Burning| work=The New York Times| date=December 13, 1888| subscription=yes| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1888/12/13/archives/a-big-theatre-burning-the-chicago-opera-house-threatened-with.html}}</ref>
The last performance at the building was the stage play ''The Escape'' by Paul Armstrong (later made into a film, now lost, by D.W. Griffith in 1914). Demolition on The Chicago Opera House began May 5, 1913.<ref>{{cite news| title=The Chicago Opera House Closed| work=[[Chicago Tribune|The Chicago Daily Tribune]]| date=May 4, 1913| page=4, Part 1}}</ref> The site is currently occupied by the [[Burnham Center]] (formerly known as the Conway Building), completed in 1915.<ref>{{cite web| title=Burnham Center| url=http://www.emporis.com/en/wm/bu/?id=116837| publisher=[[Emporis]]| accessdate=28 January 2016}}</ref>
==Construction== The idea for the Chicago Opera House came from Scottish-born newspaperman and financier David Henderson.<ref>{{cite book| url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/1244.html| title=Theater| work=[[The Encyclopedia of Chicago]]| last=Adler| first=Tony| year=2005| isbn=978-0226310152}}</ref> Henderson "planned the scheme and the stock – 550,000 – was subscribed in six weeks. Thus Chicago had the first fireproof, steel constructed, electric lighted theatre in the country."<ref>{{cite book| title=Who's who on the Stage| editor1-first=Walter| editor1-last=Browne| editor2-first=Frederick Arnold| editor2-last=Austin| year=1908| page=232| publisher=B.W. Dodge| location=[[New York City]]}}</ref> The construction of the Chicago Opera House was one of the earliest examples of [[General contractor|general contracting]], run by [[George A. Fuller]]. Upon completion, the [[masonry]]-clad building was 10 stories and {{convert|140|ft|m}} tall.<ref name=randall>{{cite book| first=Frank Alfred| last=Randall| editor-first=John D.| editor-last=Randall| title=History of the Development of Building Construction in Chicago| publisher=University of Illinois Press| year=1999| page=110| isbn=978-0252024160| quote=The practice of general contracting is said to have been first employed here by George A. Fuller.}}</ref>
