'''Trop Jr''' is a [[short film]] [[film festival|festival]] featuring films produced by Australians aged 15 years and younger. Trop Jr has been part of the [[Tropfest]] film festival since 2008 and is held in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] each year. Trop Jr is billed as "The Worlds Largest Short Film Festival for Kids! By Kids!".
Each year, Trop Jr has a theme of a "signature item", an item or action being incorporated in the entry films to ensure that they are unique and are made specifically for Trop Jr. The films must be seven minutes or less. The prize includes a digital camera, an ABC3 educational filmmaking experience and film and television short courses.
==History== Trop Jr has been included as part of the [[Tropfest]] program since 2008, when 8 films were entered into competition. It had been planned for three years, and has support from the Australian Children's Television Foundation, Boomerang and the Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/junior-goes-to-hollywood/2007/09/15/1189277038357.html|title=Junior goes to Hollywood|last=Timson|first=Lia|date=17 September 2007|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref>
One of the judges in 2009, when 12 films were screened, was child actor [[Brandon Walters]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/02/19/2495395.htm?site=sydney|title=Australia star joins Trop Jr judging panel|date=19 February 2009|work=702 ABC Sydney|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> Around 150 films were entered in 2010, of which 14 were finalists including two separate films by a brother and sister; the elder brother won.<ref name=rivalry>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/pick-of-the-trop-sibling-rivalry-goes-celluloid/2010/02/19/1266082354397.html|title=Pick of the Trop: sibling rivalry goes celluloid|last=Fulton|first=Adam|date=20 February 2010|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> The 2008 runner-up also made the finals in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/02/06/2484064.htm|title=Classic storylines dominate Tropfest shortlist|date=6 February 2009|work=ABC News|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> The 2011 winner, "Imagine", was inspired by [[Inception]], and was made on a camera phone for A$70 over three days.<ref name="imagine">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/filmed-on-a-phone-spy-movie-takes-out-junior-tropfest-award-20110220-1b17q.html?skin=text-only|title=Filmed on a phone, spy movie takes out junior Tropfest award|last=Davey|first=Melissa|date=21 February 2011|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> Adrian Di Salle, winner in 2013, had entered 4 times previously, never being shortlisted until his fifth winning entry. {| class="wikitable" |- ! Year ! Winner ! Runner-up ! Signature item |- | 2008 | Guy Verge Wallace, "Poor Joshua Verde"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/film/red-carpet-at-grassroots-of-australian-film/2008/02/17/1203190648692.html|title=Red carpet at grassroots of Australian film - Film - Entertainment - smh.com.au|website=www.smh.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> | Jasmin-Johanna Mobbs, "Besties"<ref name="whiz">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/our-film-whizkids-shoot-for-the-big-time-at-trop-jr/2009/01/31/1232818790534.html|title=Our film whiz-kids shoot for the big time at Trop Jr|last=Bizzaca|first=Caris|date=1 February 2009|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=26 June 2011}}</ref> | Green |- | 2009 | Gabriel Colomb, "Dry Water: The Making Of" | Andrew Mills, "Big Bad Baz" | Squeeze |- | 2010 | Peter Richardson and Josh Raish, "Every Coin Has Two Sides" | Sam Wickham, "D'Amoure Courte" | Dot |- | 2011 | Simeon Bain, "Imagine"<ref name="imagine" /> | Emily Williamson & Mayfield State School, "The Groundsman"<ref>{{Citation|last=TROPFEST|title=THE GROUNDSMAN - Trop Jr 2011 Runner Up (kids competition)|date=2011-02-27|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=56zPgdVOPaM|accessdate=2018-04-15}}</ref> | Fan |- | 2012 | Max Barden and Tim Sheehan, "Let's Make A Movie" | Yianni Rowlands, "The I Think You Stink Show"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actf.com.au/news/10060/trop-jr-2012|title=Trop Jr 2012|website=The Australian Children's Television Foundation|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> | Juice |- | 2013, Feb | Ben McCarthy, "Bumper" | Harri Gilbert & The Screen Seekers Club, "How to Make a Horror Movie" | Jump |- | 2013, Dec | Adrian Di Salle, "The Adventures Of Lucy" | Oliver Levi-Malouf, "Penelopes Penguins" | Monster |- | 2014 | Paige Bebee, "Chance" | Jobe Adams, "Buloo"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actf.com.au/news/10177/chance-wins-at-trop-jr|title=Chance wins at Trop Jr|website=The Australian Children's Television Foundation|language=en|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> | Fly |- | 2016 | Yianni Rowlands, "Chess people"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iris.theaureview.com/yianni-rowlands-four-year-filmmaking-journey-ends-with-tropfest-jr-win/|title=Yianni Rowlands Four Year Filmmaking Journey Ends With Tropfest Jr Win {{!}} The Iris|website=iris.theaureview.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> | Isaac Haigh, "Ding Dong" | Button |- |2017 | Nick Ward, "Pupils" |Jordan Blanch, "The Lemonade Stand" |Mask |- |2018 |Tadji Ulrich, "Outcasts Anonymous" |Austin Macfarlane, "The Sock Dimension"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/public-notice/tadji-ulrich-crowned-2018-trop-jr-winner/|title=TADJI ULRICH CROWNED 2018 TROP JR WINNER {{!}} FilmInk|website=www.filmink.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tropfest.org.au/blog/80|title=Tropfest|website=www.tropfest.org.au|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> |Rainbow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tropfest.org.au/blog/Entries-open|title=Tropfest|website=www.tropfest.org.au|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref> |}
